This is key! From line 192-196:
```js
// If already in a transaction, just run (no nesting — flattened)
if (this.activeTx) {
  const txCtx = this.createTransactionContext();
  return fn(txCtx);
}
```

This means `stacks.transaction` is reentrant/flattenable — if you're already inside a transaction, calling `stacks.transaction` again just runs in the same transaction. This is crucial.

This means that if the cartograph opens a `stacks.transaction`, and inside it calls `clerk.transition()` (which internally calls `stacks.transaction`), the inner transaction is just flattened into the outer one. 

The same applies to `clerk.setWritExt()` — it also gets flattened if called within an existing transaction. So the brief's requirement to wrap both `clerk.transition` and `clerk.setWritExt` in a single `stacks.transaction` works perfectly because of this flattening behavior. Now I need to check whether `clerk.transition` can actually be invoked from within a stacks transaction.

